# CARD: The War on Poverty
# =============================================================================

@lbj_gs_poverty
title: The Other America
is-card: true
card-image: img/poverty_card.png
tags: lbj_country_card
max-visits: 2

Michael Harrington wrote a book. You read it. Or you read the summary; it was long. The point stands: thirty million Americans are poor in ways that the postwar prosperity has simply not touched.

You want to end poverty. You have said you want to end poverty. The phrase "War on Poverty" is already in circulation from your State of the Union.

The question is what, exactly, the war consists of.

- @lbj_gs_poverty_oca: Create the Office of Economic Opportunity. Coordinate everything.
- @lbj_gs_poverty_jobs: Focus on job training. Practical, defensible.
- @lbj_gs_poverty_community: Community Action Programs. Local control.

@lbj_gs_poverty_oca
title: The Office of Economic Opportunity
on-arrival: lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_poverty -= 8; lbj_capital -= 14; lbj_liberals += 6; lbj_labor += 4; lbj_far_right += 5; lbj_dixiecrats -= 4

Sargent Shriver runs it. He is energetic in a way that slightly exhausts you.

The programs proliferate: Head Start, VISTA, Job Corps, Legal Services, Community Action. They work unevenly, which critics call failure and which you call the nature of large-scale social programs.

Congress will try to dismantle this for the next decade. Some of it will survive.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_gs_poverty_jobs
title: Job Corps
on-arrival: lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_poverty -= 5; lbj_capital -= 8; lbj_labor += 7; lbj_liberals += 3

Job training is politically defensible. Teaching a man to work is not welfare; it is, as you put it in the speech, a hand up, not a handout.

The Job Corps opens residential centers. Young men — mostly young men, mostly Black and brown young men from cities and rural hollows — come through and come out the other side with skills and sometimes with jobs.

The program is more limited than you wanted. It is also more durable.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_gs_poverty_community
title: Maximum Feasible Participation
on-arrival: lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_poverty -= 6; lbj_capital -= 10; lbj_liberals += 8; lbj_dixiecrats -= 6; lbj_unity -= 3

The Community Action Programs will require, by law, "maximum feasible participation" of the poor themselves. This seems reasonable, even democratic.

What it means in practice is that poor people in cities begin organizing, demanding things, running for things, making themselves politically visible in ways that the city machines did not anticipate.

Mayor Daley calls you. He is not pleased. Several other mayors call. None of them are pleased.

You explain to them that this is democracy. They explain to you that this is not what they understood democracy to mean.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: Medicare
# =============================================================================

@lbj_gs_medicare
title: Medicare
is-card: true
card-image: img/medicare_card.png
tags: lbj_country_card
view-if: lbj_ev_medicare = 0
max-visits: 2

Harry Truman proposed national health insurance in 1949. The AMA called it socialized medicine and killed it.

You are going to try something smaller: health insurance for the elderly and the poor. Medicare and Medicaid, funded through Social Security. Wilbur Mills, who chairs Ways and Means and is not always your friend, is, on this issue, moveable.

The AMA is still calling it socialized medicine.

- @lbj_gs_medicare_sign: Push it through. Sign it in Independence, Missouri — in front of Truman.
- @lbj_gs_medicare_compromise: Negotiate with the AMA. Get something.
- @lbj_gs_medicare_delay: Other priorities first.

@lbj_gs_medicare_sign
title: Independence, Missouri
on-arrival: lbj_ev_medicare = 1; lbj_gs_progress += 2; lbj_capital -= 16; lbj_liberals += 10; lbj_labor += 8; lbj_poverty -= 10; lbj_approval += 5; lbj_far_right += 6

You fly to Independence, Missouri. You sign the bill in front of Harry Truman, who is eighty years old and has waited his whole political life for this. You hand him the first two Medicare cards.

He cries. You are not going to mention that part, but he does.

Eighteen million Americans will be covered in the first year. The number will grow.

The AMA is furious. They will get over it, or they won't, and it won't matter, because the program will be too popular to repeal.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_gs_medicare_compromise
title: Working with the AMA
on-arrival: lbj_ev_medicare = 1; lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_capital -= 10; lbj_liberals += 5; lbj_poverty -= 6

The bill that passes is less generous than what you wanted, more generous than what the AMA wanted. Both sides call it a compromise, which means both sides lost something.

Fourteen million Americans are covered. The number grows more slowly.

Truman gets his card in the mail like everyone else.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_gs_medicare_delay
title: Not This Session
on-arrival: lbj_liberals -= 5; lbj_labor -= 3; lbj_capital += 5

The votes were there. They will be harder to find next year.

You have a list of things you've delayed. The list is getting long.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: The Education Act
# =============================================================================

@lbj_gs_education
title: Federal Aid to Education
is-card: true
card-image: img/education_card.png
tags: lbj_country_card
max-visits: 2

Federal aid to public schools has been blocked for decades — by the Catholic Church (opposed to funding public but not parochial schools), by segregationists (opposed to any federal involvement that might come with desegregation strings), and by conservatives (opposed on principle).

You have found a formula that threads the needle: aid follows the child, not the school. Parochial schools benefit. Segregated districts are eligible but only if they're making progress.

It is a compromise. It is also, potentially, transformational.

- @lbj_gs_education_push: Make it a priority. This changes the country in a generation.
- @lbj_gs_education_quiet: Pass it quietly. Big claims draw big opposition.

@lbj_gs_education_push
title: A Generation
on-arrival: lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_capital -= 12; lbj_liberals += 7; lbj_poverty -= 5; lbj_dixiecrats -= 3; lbj_approval += 3

The Elementary and Secondary Education Act passes. You sign it in the one-room schoolhouse in Stonewall, Texas where you first went to school, next to your first teacher.

One billion dollars for public education, most of it going to low-income districts. Head Start in every state. Books in schools that have never had enough books.

The effects will take a generation to measure. That is, you tell yourself, the nature of the right investments.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_gs_education_quiet
title: Quietly Done
on-arrival: lbj_gs_progress += 1; lbj_capital -= 8; lbj_liberals += 4; lbj_poverty -= 3

The bill passes without ceremony. This is sometimes the best way.

The money goes out. The schools get it. The results are real and unspectacular, which is how most of history's most important things work.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office


