# =============================================================================
# CARD: Richard Russell
# =============================================================================

@lbj_faction_russell
title: Senator Russell
is-card: true
card-image: img/russell_card.png
tags: lbj_party_card
max-visits: 4

He is the most powerful man in the Senate and your mentor and the primary obstacle to everything you are trying to do on civil rights, and you love him in the complicated way of political men who have been in the same foxhole for twenty years.

He is not going to change. He is seventy-something years old and he has been wrong about the most important question in American life since 1948 and he is not going to change.

What you can manage is the relationship — what he does with his votes, what he tells his colleagues about you.

- @lbj_faction_russell_charm: Work the relationship. Separate the man from his position.
- @lbj_faction_russell_confront: Tell him you're going ahead without him.
- @lbj_faction_russell_favor: Do him a favor. Pick up a chit.

@lbj_faction_russell_charm
title: The Treatment
on-arrival: lbj_dixiecrats += 5; lbj_capital -= 5; lbj_south_backlash -= 3; lbj_continuity_hints += 1

You give him the treatment. You call it that yourself, privately — the full Johnson treatment, which involves a level of physical proximity and sustained personal attention that most men find difficult to resist.

You talk about Texas. You talk about his family. You talk around the things you disagree on and through the things you agree on.

He doesn't change his vote. But he doesn't actively campaign against you this week, and in Senate terms that is a form of friendship.

Before you leave, he mentions — in the way he mentions things he wants on record between you — that he has heard some things from some people at the Pentagon that he didn't entirely understand. He says it might be worth asking Clifford about.

You ask what kind of things.

He says he'd rather not say. He shakes your hand.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_faction_russell_confront
title: Without You
on-arrival: lbj_dixiecrats -= 10; lbj_credibility += 4; lbj_liberals += 5; lbj_south_backlash += 8

You tell him directly: you are going to do this with or without the Southern bloc, and you are going to win, and he is going to be on the wrong side of history, and the question is whether he wants to be a senator who opposed it or one who at least stood aside.

He is not angry. He is sad, which is worse.

He tells you that you are making a mistake you won't be able to take back.

You know he means several things by that.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_faction_russell_favor
title: A Favor
on-arrival: lbj_dixiecrats += 8; lbj_capital -= 10; lbj_credibility -= 2

You do him a favor. It is a specific, transactional favor of the kind that Senate relationships are made of. You do not say what it is in any document.

He does you a favor in return. You do not say what it is either.

The coalition holds a little longer.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: George Wallace
# =============================================================================

@lbj_faction_wallace
title: Wallace
is-card: true
card-image: img/wallace_card.png
tags: lbj_party_card
view-if: lbj_year >= 1966
max-visits: 3

George Wallace is doing something that is going to matter and that your people don't fully understand yet. He is going to Wisconsin — Wisconsin, which is supposed to be solid — and he is getting thirty percent in the primary polls. He is not running against you on race, technically. He is running against busing, against crime, against big government, against the federal courts. He is running against a feeling.

The feeling is real. You know it's real because you're from the South, and you can read it in letters you're not showing your staff.

- @lbj_faction_wallace_ignore: Ignore him. He's a regional candidate.
- @lbj_faction_wallace_absorb: Move toward his voters. Adjust the message.
- @lbj_faction_wallace_confront: Confront the backlash directly. Name it.

@lbj_faction_wallace_ignore
title: Regional Politics
on-arrival: lbj_far_right += 8; lbj_dixiecrats -= 5; lbj_unity -= 4

He runs well enough to matter in 1968. You will be telling yourself you should have taken him more seriously.

The voters he is reaching are not coming back. The coalition your father's generation built is ending, and you can see the ending happening, and you are not sure what to do about it that doesn't involve betraying everything you've spent your presidency trying to build.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_faction_wallace_absorb
title: The Message
on-arrival: lbj_far_right -= 5; lbj_liberals -= 8; lbj_unity -= 3; lbj_credibility -= 4; lbj_dixiecrats += 4

You adjust. You talk more about crime. You talk more about order. You find ways to signal to the working-class white voters that you hear them.

The left calls you a sellout. The Wallace voters are not fully persuaded anyway. You have managed to annoy everyone without solving the problem.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_faction_wallace_confront
title: Call It What It Is
on-arrival: lbj_far_right += 5; lbj_liberals += 8; lbj_credibility += 5; lbj_dixiecrats -= 8; lbj_unity -= 5

You call it what it is. In a speech you write yourself — you draft the critical paragraph at the kitchen table at the ranch — you name the thing Wallace is doing and refuse to pretend it's something else.

The liberals love it. The Wallace voters are confirmed in their opposition. The middle wonders which side you're on.

You are on the side of the thing you said. You believe that. You also believe that believing it is not enough.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office


