@lbj_ending_collapse
title: The Breaking Point
new-page: true

There are days when countries break.

Not all at once. Not in a single dramatic moment, despite what the history books will tell your grandchildren. Countries break the way bodies do — a slow accumulation of pressures, small failures of load-bearing structures, and then a day when something that was weight-bearing is simply gone and the whole thing shifts.

The year — [+ lbj_year +] — will be taught in schools as the year the postwar American consensus ended. They will argue about what ended it: the war, the cities, the assassinations, the failure of institutions, the credibility gap, the fractures in the party. They will all be right, partially.

What they will not quite capture is the specific feeling of standing in the Oval Office in the months before it became clear, watching the instruments, knowing what the numbers meant, and not being able to find the decision that fixed it.

There was no such decision. That is the hardest thing a president can learn.

**[ENDING: THE BREAKING POINT — The Country Comes Apart]**

- @start: Play again

@lbj_ending_repudiation
title: No Confidence
new-page: true

At some point, a president who has lost the country's trust is simply a man in a building.

The approval numbers — you have never not known the approval numbers, not for a single day of your presidency — have fallen past the point where they measure popularity and into the territory where they measure something else. Legitimacy. The basic willingness of a democracy to accept the decisions of the person it elected.

[? if lbj_credibility < 30 : They don't believe what you say. Not as a partisan matter — not just Republicans, not just the movement left — but as a simple factual matter. The credibility gap became, quietly, an assumption. You are assumed to be lying until proven otherwise. Governing under that assumption is like trying to build a house while someone is taking the foundation apart. ?]

You govern out your term. The historical assessments vary. Most of them are not kind.

You go home to the Pedernales.

**[ENDING: NO CONFIDENCE — A Presidency Hollowed Out]**

- @start: Play again

@lbj_ending_vietnam_quagmire
title: The Mekong Delta
new-page: true

History will not remember what you built. History will remember the war.

That is perhaps unfair. The Great Society programs — Medicare, the Voting Rights Act, federal education funding, Head Start, a hundred other programs — will outlast you and will quietly improve the lives of tens of millions of Americans in ways that are difficult to attribute because they are structural. The counterfactual does not exist. You cannot see what poverty looks like without Medicare. You cannot see what American democracy looks like without the Voting Rights Act. So history cannot see it either, and what history cannot see, history cannot credit.

What history can see is the body count. The footage. Cronkite saying *stalemate.* The boys.

In some future decade, they will build a wall in Washington with [+ lbj_casualties +]-times-a-thousand names on it. You will not live to see it. You know it's coming.

You should have found the way out earlier. You know that too.

**[ENDING: THE WAR — Vietnam Consumes Everything]**

- @start: Play again

@lbj_ending_survived
title: January 20, 1969
new-page: true

Richard Nixon places his hand on the Bible.

You watch. Lady Bird watches. The January cold is specific and biting in the way of Washington cold, which has none of the drama of Texas cold but plenty of the unpleasantness.

You are sixty years old. You have been president for five years and fifty-seven days. You will live four more years and die at the ranch, alone, in the late afternoon, of a heart attack you had been expecting since 1955.

But that is later. Right now you are watching Nixon take the oath.

[? if lbj_gs_progress >= 5 : The Great Society is law. Most of it will survive. The programs you built — Medicare, Medicaid, the education acts, the housing legislation, Head Start — will be attacked and underfunded and occasionally dismantled at the margins, but the core will hold. Fifty years from now, Americans will receive Medicare as if it has always existed, which is the best thing you can say about a government program: that it becomes invisible because it becomes necessary. ?]

[? if lbj_cr_progress >= 3 : The Civil Rights Act. The Voting Rights Act. Whatever else the history books take from you, they cannot take those. You said *we shall overcome* in front of a joint session of Congress and you meant it and the legislation was real and the people who needed it most knew it was real. ?]

[? if lbj_vietnam >= 60 : The war is still going. Nixon inherits it. He will say he has a plan. You know he doesn't. But it is his problem now. That is not comfort. It is just fact. ?]

[? if lbj_vietnam < 40 : The war is winding down. Not quickly, not cleanly, but the numbers are going the right direction. You wish you had found this exit earlier. You wish a lot of things. ?]

The Marine helicopter lifts off from the Capitol lawn. You and Lady Bird fly back to Texas.

*You go home.*

**[ENDING: JANUARY 20, 1969 — The Weight Lifted]**

- @start: Play again

@lbj_ending_great_society
title: What Gets Built
new-page: true

You will be remembered for the Great Society. Not only for the Great Society — the war is in there, the choices that couldn't be unmade, the credibility gap, the coalition that broke — but the Great Society will be there too, durable and large, the way big things are when they're built out of the right materials.

Medicare. Medicaid. The Civil Rights Act. The Voting Rights Act. The Elementary and Secondary Education Act. The Fair Housing Act. Head Start. Public broadcasting. The National Endowment for the Arts. Clean air legislation. Clean water legislation. The Immigration Act that ended the national-origins quota system. The Older Americans Act. Food stamps.

You did this. In five years. While a war was eating your attention and your budget and your political capital. While the country was coming apart in ways you could feel but not always see clearly.

It will be a long time before anyone tries to build anything this large again. You suspect — you do not say this to anyone — that it may be a very long time indeed.

But it's there. It's law. It exists in the world.

Lady Bird says: *You are not the worst president we've had, Lyndon.*

You say that is not the bar you were aiming for.

She says: *But you cleared it. You cleared it by a lot.*

**[ENDING: WHAT GETS BUILT — The Great Society Stands]**

